---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Nav from '../components/Nav.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Unified Workflow — HPS AI Hub"
  description="One workflow: SDD handles planning, OmO handles execution, Engram persists everything across sessions."
>
  <Nav />

  <main class="main">

    <!-- ── Hero ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
    <section class="hero" data-animate="fade-up">
      <div class="hero-inner">
        <p class="eyebrow">06 — Unified Workflow</p>
        <h1 class="hero-title">SDD Planning +<br/>OmO Execution</h1>
        <p class="hero-lede">
          One workflow, not five. <strong>SDD</strong> (gentle-ai) handles planning — what to build.
          <strong>OmO</strong> handles execution — how to build it, with the right model for each task.
          <strong>Engram</strong> persists everything across sessions.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ── §1 IntentGate (Phase 0) ──────────────────────────────────── -->
    <section class="content-section" id="intentgate">
      <div class="section-inner">
        <h2 class="section-title" data-animate="fade-up">IntentGate — Phase 0</h2>

        <p class="prose">
          Before any category routing happens, <strong>IntentGate</strong> runs a
          lightweight classifier that reads user intent semantically — not lexically.
          The output is a structured routing decision: intent class, size tier, and
          suggested category. Only then does the category router pick a worker.
        </p>

        <pre class="diagram" data-animate="fade-up">USER types in OpenCode
  │
  ▼
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│ IntentGate · fast classifier (Haiku or Mini)    │
│   · semantic intent analysis                     │
│   · size tier detection                          │
│   · category suggestion                          │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
  │
  ▼
{"{ intent, size_tier, category, confidence }"}
  │
  ├── confidence ≥ 0.8   → direct to category router
  ├── confidence 0.5–0.8 → brief Prometheus clarification
  └── confidence &lt; 0.5   → full Prometheus interview</pre>

        <p class="prose">
          The gate is <strong>read-only</strong> — no side effects, no tool calls.
          It exists to prevent OmO from routing code-gen work to the wrong category
          (a typo fix going to <code>ultrabrain</code> when <code>quick</code>
          would do) or triggering full SDD on work that should stay trivial.
        </p>

        <div class="callout callout-info" data-animate="fade-up">
          <strong>Why Phase 0:</strong> previous versions of OmO routed by keyword
          match. IntentGate adds semantic classification — the same phrase can mean
          different things across project contexts, and the gate reads that context
          from Engram before committing to a routing decision.
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ── §2 Workflow Routing ──────────────────────────────────────── -->
    <section class="content-section">
      <div class="section-inner">
        <h2 class="section-title" data-animate="fade-up">Workflow Routing</h2>

        <pre class="diagram" data-animate="fade-up">USER types in OpenCode
  │
  ▼
IntentGate (Phase 0 — see §1)
  │ outputs: {"{ intent, size_tier, category }"}
  │
  ├─ /session-{"'{domain}'"}        ← Domain preset (skills + models + MCPs)
  │
  ├─ TRIVIAL ("fix typo")    → Direct execution (category: quick)
  │                              Model: GPT-5.4 Mini or Qwen 3 Coder (FREE)
  │
  ├─ MEDIUM ("add button")   → SDD-lite: explore → apply → verify
  │                              Model: Sonnet for all phases
  │
  ├─ LARGE ("build feature") → SDD FULL + OmO execution
  │   ├── PLAN (SDD):   explore → propose → spec → design → tasks
  │   │   Models:        Sonnet    Opus      Sonnet  Opus    Sonnet
  │   │   All persists to Engram — survives sessions + compaction
  │   │
  │   ├── EXECUTE (OmO): Atlas reads tasks → category-routes workers
  │   │   ├── UI task         → Gemini 3.1 Pro (visual-engineering)
  │   │   ├── API task        → Sonnet / Qwen 3 Coder (FREE)
  │   │   ├── Architecture    → GPT-5.4 (ultrabrain)
  │   │   ├── Docs task       → Gemini Flash (writing)
  │   │   └── Trivial task    → GPT-5.4 Mini (quick)
  │   │   + Hash-anchored edits (68.3% success)
  │   │   + Wisdom accumulation (learnings pass forward)
  │   │   + Ralph Loop: refuses to stop until 100% done
  │   │
  │   └── VERIFY (SDD): compare implementation vs specs
  │       Model: Sonnet · Reports: CRITICAL / WARNING / SUGGESTION
  │
  ├─ EMERGENCY ("prod down") → Ralph Loop: persistent until fixed
  │
  └─ RESULTS → Engram → HPS-Dream (nightly consolidation at 03:00)</pre>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ── §3 OmO Execution Modes ───────────────────────────────────── -->
    <section class="content-section" id="omo-execution-modes">
      <div class="section-inner">
        <h2 class="section-title" data-animate="fade-up">OmO Execution Modes</h2>

        <p class="prose">
          Once tasks exist, OmO runs them under one of four execution modes. The
          mode is picked at dispatch time based on size tier, risk level, and whether
          the session is resuming previous work.
        </p>

        <div class="table-wrap" data-animate="fade-up">
          <table class="routing-table" role="table">
            <thead>
              <tr>
                <th>Mode</th>
                <th>Trigger</th>
                <th>Behavior</th>
                <th>Size tier fit</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr>
                <td><code>standard</code></td>
                <td>default dispatch</td>
                <td>Atlas delegates by category; workers run one-shot; stop on first failure</td>
                <td>TRIVIAL, MEDIUM</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><code>ralph-loop</code></td>
                <td>explicit flag or EMERGENCY intent</td>
                <td>Persistent execution — retries until 100% done or hard-stop signal</td>
                <td>LARGE, INITIATIVE, urgent fixes</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><code>ULTRAWORK (ULW)</code></td>
                <td><code>/ultrawork</code> or <code>ULW</code> flag</td>
                <td>Agent self-directs — skips SDD planning phases, picks decomposition itself</td>
                <td>LARGE with settled architecture</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><code>resume</code></td>
                <td><code>/start-work</code></td>
                <td>Reads <code>boulder.json</code> state; picks up at last saved checkpoint</td>
                <td>any tier after interruption</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h3 class="subsection-title">Ralph Loop contract</h3>

        <pre class="diagram" data-animate="fade-up">while task.status != "done":
    attempt = worker.execute(task)
    if attempt.failed:
        analyze_failure(attempt)
        adjust_approach()
        # NO STOP — retry with new approach
    elif attempt.partial:
        complete_remaining_work()
    else:  # attempt.done
        task.status = "done"
        update wisdom_notepad</pre>

        <p class="prose">
          Ralph Loop refuses to stop until work is 100% complete. Used for emergencies
          (prod down) or LARGE changes where partial completion is worse than retry
          cost. The agent analyzes each failure, adjusts approach, and tries again —
          no "failed once, give up" behavior.
        </p>

        <h3 class="subsection-title">ULTRAWORK (ULW)</h3>

        <p class="prose">
          <code>ULTRAWORK</code> is the mode where the agent skips planning phases
          entirely and self-directs from intent to completion. Appropriate when the
          architecture is settled and the task is large but internally coherent —
          for example, implementing a well-understood pattern across many files. The
          agent owns the decomposition; SDD skips <code>explore</code> →
          <code>propose</code> → <code>design</code> and goes straight to
          <code>apply</code> with continuous wisdom accumulation.
        </p>

        <h3 class="subsection-title">Wisdom Notepad</h3>

        <p class="prose">
          Every completed task appends to <code>.sisyphus/notepads/</code> — a
          per-project journal containing learnings (what worked, what failed),
          decisions (what was chosen and why), and open issues (deferred problems,
          known edge cases). Each subsequent task reads previous notepads before
          starting — wisdom accumulates forward across the project.
        </p>

        <p class="prose">
          Notepads coexist with Engram, not compete: <strong>Engram</strong> holds
          queryable structured facts (topic keys, semantic search);
          <strong>Wisdom Notepad</strong> holds narrative journal entries. Both feed
          context to the next agent.
        </p>

        <h3 class="subsection-title">Hash-anchored edits</h3>

        <p class="prose">
          Standard LLM edits (find-and-replace by content) succeed ~6.7% of the
          time on large codebases. OmO pins edits to content hashes instead —
          <strong>68.3% success rate</strong>. Wrong-file or stale-context edits
          become detectable and revertible before they execute.
        </p>

        <h3 class="subsection-title">Resume via /start-work</h3>

        <p class="prose">
          Long-running OmO sessions checkpoint state to <code>boulder.json</code>
          at every phase transition. Running <code>/start-work</code> in a fresh
          session reads this file, restores context, and resumes at the last
          checkpoint. No need to re-run SDD from scratch when you come back after
          lunch.
        </p>

        <pre class="diagram" data-animate="fade-up">boulder.json (checkpoint schema):
{"{"}
  "change": "hps-feature-name",
  "phase": "apply",
  "last_checkpoint": "2026-04-17T14:32:10Z",
  "completed_tasks": [1, 2, 3],
  "current_task": 4,
  "engram_refs": ["sdd/hps-feature-name/apply-progress"],
  "wisdom_notepad_cursor": 127
{"}"}</pre>

        <div class="callout callout-info" data-animate="fade-up">
          <strong>External references (benchmark only, NOT adopted):</strong>
          <code>Kyros</code> (CC Leak — 15-second background polling) and
          <code>Ultra Plan</code> (CC Leak — 30-minute continuous processing tier)
          share architectural DNA with Ralph Loop and ULTRAWORK respectively. HPS
          OS does not adopt the 15s polling model (conflicts with IntentGate's
          intent-gated philosophy) nor the 30min ceiling (OmO has no hard session
          limit). Listed here for comparison, not as features to adopt.
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ── §4 Enhanced SDD Protocol ─────────────────────────────────── -->
    <section class="content-section">
      <div class="section-inner">
        <h2 class="section-title" data-animate="fade-up">Enhanced SDD for OpenCode — Opt-in Quality Gates</h2>

        <div class="callout callout-warning" data-animate="fade-up">
          <strong>Scope rule:</strong> In <strong>Claude Code</strong> use ONLY the canonical SDD pipeline above.
          The Enhanced SDD integration with Prometheus/Metis/Momus is <strong>OpenCode-only</strong> —
          it invokes real OmO agents that don't exist in Claude Code. One host = one workflow.
          Portability is preserved via engram topic keys regardless.
        </div>

        <p class="prose">
          Gentleman SDD and OmO Prometheus/Metis/Momus overlap in the planning layer — both produce
          a plan describing what to build. They differ in decomposition strategy: SDD is phase-based
          with sequential artifacts, P+M+M is role-based with iterative interview/review loops.
          Rather than picking one or the other, Enhanced SDD <strong>fuses</strong> them by keeping
          SDD's phase structure and topic key discipline while injecting P+M+M behaviors at specific
          integration points — but only in OpenCode where the real agents exist natively.
        </p>

        <h3 class="subsection-title">Opt-in Phases in the SDD DAG</h3>

        <pre class="diagram" data-animate="fade-up">The 3 opt-in phases inserted into the canonical SDD DAG (OpenCode + OmO only):

explore
  │
  ├──▶ INTERVIEW ◀── (Prometheus: back-and-forth clarification)
  │
  ▼
propose
  │
  ├──▶ GAP-ANALYZE ◀── (Metis: scope creep, hidden intent, AI-slop)
  │
  ▼
[spec ∥ design]
  │
  ├──▶ PLAN-REVIEW ◀── (Momus: OKAY/REJECT loop on 4 criteria)
  │         │
  │    (loop back if REJECT — no max retry)
  ▼         ▼
tasks ◀────┘
  │
  ▼
apply → verify → archive</pre>

        <h3 class="subsection-title">Phase Contracts</h3>

        <div class="table-wrap" data-animate="fade-up">
          <table class="routing-table" role="table">
            <thead>
              <tr>
                <th>Phase</th>
                <th>Purpose</th>
                <th>Backing Agent</th>
                <th>Model</th>
                <th>Output Topic Key</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr>
                <td><code>sdd-interview</code></td>
                <td>Interactive clarification before propose. Identifies ambiguities, edge cases, implicit constraints. READ-ONLY.</td>
                <td>Prometheus</td>
                <td>Opus / Kimi K2.5</td>
                <td><code>{"sdd/{change}/interview-transcript"}</code></td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><code>sdd-gap-analyze</code></td>
                <td>Gap analysis after propose. Catches scope creep, hidden intent, AI-slop placeholders, missing acceptance criteria, uncaught edge cases.</td>
                <td>Metis</td>
                <td>Opus</td>
                <td><code>{"sdd/{change}/gap-analysis"}</code></td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><code>sdd-plan-review</code></td>
                <td>Quality gate before tasks. Validates plan vs 4 criteria: clarity, verification, context, big picture. OKAY/REJECT loop with NO max retry.</td>
                <td>Momus</td>
                <td>GPT-5.4 xhigh</td>
                <td><code>{"sdd/{change}/plan-review"}</code></td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h3 class="subsection-title">Activation by Size Tier</h3>

        <div class="table-wrap" data-animate="fade-up">
          <table class="routing-table" role="table">
            <thead>
              <tr>
                <th>Tier</th>
                <th>interview</th>
                <th>gap-analyze</th>
                <th>plan-review</th>
                <th>Rationale</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr><td>TRIVIAL</td><td>✗</td><td>✗</td><td>✗</td><td>Overkill for typo fixes</td></tr>
              <tr><td>MEDIUM</td><td>✗</td><td>✗</td><td>✗</td><td>Canonical SDD is sufficient</td></tr>
              <tr><td>LARGE</td><td>optional</td><td>✓ on</td><td>✓ on</td><td>Big changes benefit from gap check + plan review</td></tr>
              <tr><td>INITIATIVE</td><td>✓ on</td><td>✓ on</td><td>✓ on</td><td>Multi-change work requires full quality gates</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h3 class="subsection-title">The Plan-Review Loop (Momus-style)</h3>

        <p class="prose">
          The most important Enhanced SDD contribution: <strong>moving bug detection to the plan,
          not the code</strong>. In canonical SDD, if specs have problems, they surface during
          <code>verify</code> — after implementation. Momus moves this check BEFORE <code>apply</code>:
        </p>

        <pre class="diagram" data-animate="fade-up">design → plan-review
             │
             ▼
          OKAY? ──── yes ──▶ tasks
             │
             no
             │
             ▼
         REJECT reason
             │
             ├── design-level  → re-run sdd-design with feedback
             ├── spec-level    → re-run sdd-spec with feedback
             └── propose-level → re-run sdd-propose with feedback (cascade)
             │
             ▼
         loop back to plan-review (no max retry)</pre>

        <p class="prose">
          <strong>Value:</strong> catches ~80% of bugs that would normally surface in
          <code>verify</code>, but BEFORE spending tokens on <code>apply</code>. Rewriting a spec
          costs ~1/10 of rewriting code + re-verify. Overhead per LARGE change with all 3 phases
          active: ~50–80k tokens + 5–10 min on a change that normally costs 300–500k tokens in
          apply — <strong>5–15% overhead for significant re-work reduction</strong>.
        </p>

        <h3 class="subsection-title">Extended Topic Keys (OpenCode only)</h3>

        <pre class="diagram" data-animate="fade-up">{"sdd/{change}/"}{`
  ├── explore
  ├── interview-transcript      ← NEW (Prometheus)
  ├── propose
  ├── gap-analysis              ← NEW (Metis)
  ├── spec
  ├── design
  ├── design-amendments         (if user overrides)
  ├── plan-review               ← NEW (Momus, with retry history)
  ├── tasks
  ├── apply-progress
  ├── verify-report
  └── archive-report`}</pre>

        <div class="callout callout-info" data-animate="fade-up">
          <strong>Portability:</strong> a change can start in Claude Code (canonical SDD only) and
          continue in OpenCode (enhanced phases added mid-stream). Engram topic keys are portable
          across hosts — the enhanced observations simply don't appear in the trail when running
          canonical. Full protocol: engram topic key <code>architecture/enhanced-sdd-opencode-protocol</code>,
          plus <code>AGENTS.md</code> §Enhanced SDD Protocol.
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ── §5 Domain Sessions ───────────────────────────────────────── -->
    <section class="content-section">
      <div class="section-inner">
        <h2 class="section-title" data-animate="fade-up">Domain Sessions</h2>

        <p class="prose">
          Each domain has a preset that loads the right skills, models, and MCPs. Switch
          mid-project — Engram keeps context. Compose multiple domains for cross-cutting projects.
        </p>

        <div class="table-wrap" data-animate="fade-up">
          <table class="routing-table" role="table">
            <thead>
              <tr>
                <th>Session Command</th>
                <th>Skills Loaded</th>
                <th>Model Bias</th>
                <th>MCPs Active</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr><td><code>/session-fullstack</code></td><td>nextjs-15, react-19, tailwind-4, prisma, supabase</td><td>Sonnet for code, Gemini for UI</td><td>Vercel, Supabase</td></tr>
              <tr><td><code>/session-proptech</code></td><td>hps-sevilla-pms, hps-casa-brunelli, stripe, supabase</td><td>Opus for fiscal rules</td><td>Supabase, Stripe</td></tr>
              <tr><td><code>/session-iot</code></td><td>home-assistant, n8n-workflow, hps-iot</td><td>Gemini Pro for API docs</td><td>Home Assistant</td></tr>
              <tr><td><code>/session-cybersecurity</code></td><td>owasp-security, hps-security</td><td>Opus for analysis</td><td>GitHub</td></tr>
              <tr><td><code>/session-marketing</code></td><td>agency-agents marketing profiles</td><td>Gemini for research, Flash for copy</td><td>Exa</td></tr>
              <tr><td><code>/session-deep-learning</code></td><td>hps-ml, Context7</td><td>Gemini Pro (1M context for papers)</td><td>Context7</td></tr>
              <tr><td><code>/session-financial</code></td><td>hps-fiscal-es, stripe-best-practices</td><td>Opus for fiscal rules</td><td>Stripe</td></tr>
              <tr><td><code>/session-business</code></td><td>agency-agents finance/PM profiles</td><td>Gemini for data, Sonnet for reports</td><td>Supabase</td></tr>
              <tr><td><code>/session-compose X+Y</code></td><td>Combines multiple session presets</td><td>Mixed based on task</td><td>All from combined sessions</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <div class="callout callout-info" data-animate="fade-up">
          <strong>Connecting sessions:</strong> <code>SWITCH</code> — change session mid-project,
          Engram persists between. <code>COMPOSE</code> — load multiple domains at once for
          cross-cutting work. <code>PARALLEL</code> — background agent runs in a different domain
          session via tmux while you work in another. <code>RESUME</code> — run
          <code>/start-work</code> in any domain to restore a prior session from
          <code>boulder.json</code> (see §3).
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

  </main>

  <Footer />
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  /* ── Main wrapper ──────────────────────────────────────────────────── */

  .main {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
  }

  /* ── Hero ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── */

  .hero {
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  }

  .hero-inner {
    max-width: var(--container-max);
    margin-inline: auto;
    padding-block: var(--space-24);
    padding-inline: var(--space-6);
  }

  .eyebrow {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: var(--font-size-xs);
    letter-spacing: var(--tracking-wide);
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--color-text-subtle);
    margin: 0 0 var(--space-6);
  }

  .hero-title {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: var(--font-size-5xl);
    font-weight: 300;
    letter-spacing: var(--tracking-tight);
    line-height: 1.05;
    color: var(--color-text);
    margin: 0 0 var(--space-6);
    max-width: 20ch;
  }

  .hero-lede {
    font-size: var(--font-size-md);
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    max-width: var(--content-max);
    margin: 0;
    line-height: 1.6;
  }

  /* ── Content sections ──────────────────────────────────────────────── */

  .content-section {
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  }

  .section-inner {
    max-width: var(--container-max);
    margin-inline: auto;
    padding-block: var(--space-24);
    padding-inline: var(--space-6);
  }

  .section-title {
    font-size: var(--font-size-2xl);
    font-weight: 300;
    letter-spacing: var(--tracking-snug);
    color: var(--color-text);
    margin: 0 0 var(--space-12);
  }

  .subsection-title {
    font-size: var(--font-size-lg);
    font-weight: 400;
    letter-spacing: var(--tracking-snug);
    color: var(--color-text);
    margin: var(--space-16) 0 var(--space-6);
  }

  /* ── Prose ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── */

  .prose {
    font-size: var(--font-size-base);
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    max-width: var(--content-max);
    margin: 0 0 var(--space-8);
    line-height: 1.7;
  }

  .prose strong {
    color: var(--color-text);
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  .prose code {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: var(--font-size-sm);
    background: var(--color-surface);
    padding: var(--space-0-5) var(--space-1);
    border-radius: var(--radius-sm);
  }

  /* ── ASCII Diagrams ────────────────────────────────────────────────── */

  .diagram {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: var(--font-size-sm);
    line-height: 1.5;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    background: var(--color-surface);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    padding: var(--space-4);
    border-radius: var(--radius-md);
    overflow-x: auto;
    -webkit-overflow-scrolling: touch;
    margin: 0 0 var(--space-8);
    white-space: pre;
  }

  /* ── Tables (reuses models.astro pattern) ──────────────────────────── */

  .table-wrap {
    overflow-x: auto;
    -webkit-overflow-scrolling: touch;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-6);
  }

  .routing-table {
    width: 100%;
    border-collapse: collapse;
    font-size: var(--font-size-sm);
  }

  .routing-table th,
  .routing-table td {
    text-align: left;
    padding: var(--space-3) var(--space-4);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  }

  .routing-table thead th {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: var(--font-size-xs);
    letter-spacing: var(--tracking-wide);
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--color-text-subtle);
    border-bottom: 2px solid var(--color-border);
  }

  .routing-table td {
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    line-height: 1.5;
